85
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:51,600
They're not bound to each other.

86
00:03:51,980 --> 00:03:54,920
Even if they accidentally got bound to each other,

87
00:03:55,080 --> 00:04:00,520
the high temperatures out there would cause collisions,

88
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:03,020
the collisions being energy,

89
00:04:03,020 --> 00:04:04,500
collisions between atoms.

90
00:04:04,840 --> 00:04:08,160
And also another thing which is out there is photons.

91
00:04:08,740 --> 00:04:11,440
Those photons are all around us,

92
00:04:11,560 --> 00:04:13,840
but when we go backward in time,

93
00:04:13,980 --> 00:04:16,360
those photons have shorter wavelength,

94
00:04:16,740 --> 00:04:18,129
and the shorter wavelength means

95
00:04:18,129 --> 00:04:19,519
that they're much more energetic,

96
00:04:19,680 --> 00:04:22,940
so what's going on out in the surface out here

97
00:04:22,940 --> 00:04:24,300
is it's full of high energy,

98
00:04:24,440 --> 00:04:25,860
not very high energy photons,

99
00:04:26,180 --> 00:04:28,560
but X-rays basically.

100
00:04:29,460 --> 00:04:30,540
X-rays,

101
00:04:32,300 --> 00:04:33,800
X-ray photons,

102
00:04:34,560 --> 00:04:36,820
and there are more X-ray photons.

103
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:37,240
In fact,

104
00:04:37,240 --> 00:04:38,840
most of the particles out there

105
00:04:38,840 --> 00:04:40,140
are these X-ray photons.

106
00:04:40,520 --> 00:04:42,280
By a factor of about

107
00:04:43,560 --> 00:04:46,040
10 to the eighth or something like that,

108
00:04:46,200 --> 00:04:48,420
most of the particles out there are photons.

109
00:04:49,280 --> 00:04:50,580
That's also true today.

110
00:04:50,740 --> 00:04:52,640
Most of the particles in the universe are photons,

111
00:04:52,980 --> 00:04:55,640
but the photons are so low energy today

112
00:04:55,640 --> 00:04:58,190
that they're not a significant part

113
00:04:58,190 --> 00:05:00,740
of the energy of the universe,

114
00:05:00,960 --> 00:05:02,500
but at that time,

115
00:05:02,500 --> 00:05:03,670
they were a significant part

116
00:05:03,670 --> 00:05:04,840
of the energy of the universe,

117
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:06,200
so it's also full of photons,

118
00:05:06,820 --> 00:05:10,640
and if by accident an atom happened to form,

119
00:05:10,800 --> 00:05:11,240
you know,

120
00:05:11,240 --> 00:05:13,100
an electron happened to get trapped,

121
00:05:15,760 --> 00:05:17,860
very shortly it would become,

122
00:05:17,860 --> 00:05:19,240
it would collide with a photon

123
00:05:19,740 --> 00:05:21,060
and get reionized,

124
00:05:21,420 --> 00:05:24,900
and so what's out there is mostly ionized gas,

125
00:05:25,180 --> 00:05:26,640
and ionized gas,

126
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:29,840
the one thing that it's not is transparent.

127
00:05:30,940 --> 00:05:34,360
Ionized gas is an electrical conductor.

128
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:38,800
Electrical conductors respond to electric fields

129
00:05:38,800 --> 00:05:40,980
by sloshing back and forth

130
00:05:40,980 --> 00:05:42,720
and re-emit radiation,

131
00:05:43,120 --> 00:05:44,760
and basically they're opaque,

132
00:05:44,980 --> 00:05:47,240
so out beyond some distance here

133
00:05:47,860 --> 00:05:49,300
the universe is opaque,

134
00:05:49,620 --> 00:05:53,940
it's opaque to us,

135
00:05:54,100 --> 00:05:56,640
and so we can't see anything

136
00:05:56,640 --> 00:05:59,180
behind that surface of last scattering.

137
00:05:59,540 --> 00:06:02,530
The surface of last scattering is a

138
00:06:02,530 --> 00:06:05,520
place like the surface of the sun

139
00:06:05,520 --> 00:06:08,140
where you go from opaque to transparent,

140
00:06:08,360 --> 00:06:11,000
and it happens reasonably suddenly,

141
00:06:14,120 --> 00:06:15,520
reasonably suddenly,

142
00:06:16,859 --> 00:06:20,360
basically when the temperature cools down

143
00:06:20,360 --> 00:06:23,180
